DBMS v/s File System
The file system has numerous issues, which were resolved with the help of DBMS. The issues with the file system are:

1- Physical Access Management: Users are responsible for managing the physical details required to access the database.
2- File System Suitability: File systems are effective for handling small databases but lack efficiency for larger ones.
3 -Concurrency Issues: For large databases, the operating system struggles to manage concurrency effectively, leading to potential conflicts.
4- Single-User Access: In a file system, only one user can access the entire dataset at a time, limiting scalability and multi-user functionality.
5- Data access: In a file system, accessing data was difficult and insecure as well. Accessing data concurrently was not possible.
6- No Backup and Recovery: There is no backup and recovery in the file system, which can lead to data loss.


Entity: The entity is a real-world object, represented using a rectangular box.

Strong Entity: A strong entity set has a primary key and all the tuples of the set can be identified using that primary key
Weak entity: When an entity does not have sufficient attributes to form a primary key. Weak entities are associated with another strong entity set also known as identifying an entity. A weak entity's existence depends upon the existence of its identifying entity. The weak entity is represented using a double-lined or bold-lined rectangle. 
